What I learned:
-Wazuh consists of multiple parts that work together
-Wazuh dashboard is accessed through HTTPS on port 443, not normal HTTP
-Wazuh agents need network connectivity back to the manager before they can report logs
-TCP 1514 is used for Wazuh agent communication
-TCP 1515 is used for agent enrollment
-The order of firewall rules matters
-In a segmented network, firewall rules have to allow only the required traffic while keeping the DMZ isolated
-nc -vz is useful for testing if a specific TCP port is reachable through the firewall
-systemctl status is not the best option for seeing root causes of agent errors, Wazuh's own ossec.log shows more specifics
-Wazuh alerts are based on logs it receives, not just any network traffic
-Nmap scans do not create SIEM alerts by default
-SSH brute-force attempts generate authentication logs, which Wazuh detects and turns into alerts
-There are many useful fields to use when investigating alerts, such as agent.name, rule.description, rule.level, rule.id, data.srcip, full_log, and location
-The dashboard can lag or require refreshes, tailing /var/ossec/logs/alerts/alerts.log is useful when confirming whether Wazuh is detecting something




